    "content": "January 18, 1878 Chen Jiongming born in Haifeng, GuangdongAugust 1908 Chen graduates from Academy of Law and Political Science at CantonOctober 14, 1909 First annual session, Guangdong Provincial AssemblyFebruary 12, 1910 Revolt of the Canton New ArmyFebruary 1910–October 1911 Assassination Corps activeMay 23, 1910 First extraordinary session, Guangdong Provincial AssemblyOctober 3, 1910 Second annual session, Guangdong Provincial AssemblyMarch-April 1911 Publication of the revolutionary journalKe baoMarch 22-April 13, 1911 Second extraordinary session, Guangdong Provincial AssemblyMarch 30, 1911 Canton celebrates gambling-suppression victoryApril 27, 1911 Canton uprisingOctober 10, 1911 The Wuchang Revolt beginsOctober 22, 1911 Third annual session, Guangdong Provincial AssemblyNovember 6, 1911 The battle at Huizhou is engagedNovember 9, 1911 Guangdong declares independenceNovember 1911-August 1913 First Republican administration in Canton establishedJuly 18-August 4,1913 The Second Revolution begins — First campaign against Yuan ShikaiAugust 1913-December 1915 Chen exiled in MalaysiaJanuary 18, 1915 Japan pressures Yuan’s government with Twenty-one DemandsFebruary 25, 1915 Chen joins with Huang Xing et al. to halt anti-Yuan campaignOctober 15. 1915 Chen explains why he declines to join Sun’s new party in JapanDecember 15. 1915 Yuan announces his intention to become emperorJanuary-June 1916 Second anti-Yuan campaignJune 6, 1916 Yuan Shikai dies — end of the Second RevolutionJune 23, 1917 Constitution Protection movement beginsJune-August, 1918 The Fujian campaignAugust 1918-November 1920 Chen administers “Little Model China” in southern FujianApril 20, 1919 First emissary arrives from Soviet RussiaMay 4, 1919 New Culture movement beginsAugust-November, 1920 Chen initiates the campaign to return to GuangdongNovember 29, 1920 Chen welcomes Sun Yat-sen back to CantonNovember 1920-January 1923 Chen administers the reconstruction of GuangdongMay 5, 1921 Sun is inaugurated as president-extraordinary in CantonJune-September, 1921 The Guangxi campaignAugust 18, 1921 Theqiaotelegram episodeOctober 15, 1921 Sun leaves Canton on the Northern ExpeditionMarch 21, 1922 Chen’s chief of staff, General Deng Keng, assassinatedApril 1922 Sun suddenly returns to Canton and forces Chen to retire to East GuangdongMay 16, 1922 Hong Kong newspapers publish Chen’s reconstruction planJune 1–2, 1922 Old parliament is restored and Northern president Xu Shichang resignsJune 3, 1922 President of Peking University appeals to Sun to resign from the Southern presidencyJune 14, 1922 Guangdong Army requests Sun’s resignation from the Southern presidencyJune 16–17, 1922 June 16 Incident: Guangdong Army rebels in Canton and Sun bombards the cityAugust 8, 1922 Sun leaves CantonAugust 15, 1922 Chen returns to CantonJanuary 1923 Sun’s mercenary troops invade Guangdong and Chen is forced to retire a second time to East GuangdongMay 28-October 27, 1923 The siege of HuizhouJuly-August 1923 Chen campaigns into southern FujianNovember 18–19, 1923 Battle of the Canton suburbsApril-September 1924 Wu Zhihui tries to reconcile Chen and SunMay 1924 First Swatow ConferenceOctober 15, 1924 The Xiguan MassacreOctober-December 1924 Cantonese movement to expel SunNovember 1924 Second Swatow Conference — Chen plans to retake CantonMarch-April 1925 First East River campaignFebruary 28, 1925 Chen’s representatives attend meetings of Zhigong Association in Victoria, CanadaMarch 12, 1925 Sun Yat-sen diesJune-July 1925 Tang Jiyao’s Yunnanese Federalist Army defeatedJune-November 1925 Second East River campaignOctober 10, 1925 Zhigong Association formally reorganized as Zhigong Party of the Americas-Chen elected as chairman and Tang Jiyao of Yunnan as vice-chairmanFebruary 1926 Headquarters of Zhigong Party moves to Hong Kong — Intense effort to extend recruitment among overseas Chinese in Southeast Asia.July 1926 Chiang Kai-shek’s Northern Expeditionary Army enters Hunan — The Federalist movement in mainland China is defeatedWinter 1927 Chen publishesA Proposal for the Unification of ChinaDecember 1928 Chen meets with Duan Qirui and Northern leaders to form a Grand Republican AllianceSeptember 18, 1931 The Mukden Incident — Japanese forces invade ManchuriaDecember 1, 1931 Chen publishes an open letter to the Chinese peopleSeptember 22, 1933 Chen dies in Hong KongApril 3, 1935 Chen is buried in Huizhou, Guangdong (Excerpt fromChen Jiongming and the federalist movementby Leslie H. Dingyan Chen)",
